    id: 11,
    title: "Hypocrisy and Praise Addiction",
    excerpt: "Exploring Jesus' teaching on hypocrisy and the dangers of seeking human praise.",
    date: "November 7, 2023",
    author: "Rev. Hermawan",
    category: "Sermon",
    content: `
### Hypocrisy and Praise Addiction
Matthew 23:1-12

“Then Jesus said to the crowds and to his disciples, 2 “The scribes and the Pharisees sit on Moses’ seat, 3 so do and observe whatever they tell you, but not the works they do. For they preach, but do not practice. 4 They tie up heavy burdens, hard to bear, and lay them on people’s shoulders, but they themselves are not willing to move them with their finger.”

The seat of Moses is a term that they are teachers of the Law seen, but to only teach but do is hypocrisy. What about what Rabbi Jesus taught? The word burden is related to Matthew 11:30. Jesus gave a light burden what is it? It is faith. Peter and the apostles decided not to impose circumcision as it was mandatory for those who were not Jews to be circumcised and obey the law of Moses. “9 He made no difference between us and them, having purified their hearts by faith. 10 Why then do you want to tempt God by putting a yoke on the disciples’ neck, which neither our fathers nor we ourselves could bear?” (Acts 15:9-10 ITB) Matthew 5 is clear that Jesus is the fulfilment of the law.

“5 They do all their deeds to be seen by others. For they make their phylacteries broad and their fringes long, 6 and they love the place of honor at feasts and the best seats in the synagogues 7 and greetings in the marketplaces and being called rabbi by others.”

Verses 5-7 are about the public space. When one no longer desires an inward heart attitude but an outward appearance and thirsts for honour, then he is meanwhile not serving God but gratifying himself and making himself the idol of many.
Jesus’ description of the Pharisees’ hypocrisy is very clear. Why did the Pharisees become hypocrites? Honor is like an opiate. J.T. O Donnel wrote, “As a matter of human nature, we like the feeling of being liked or praised. This concept is very evident in how addicted we are to social media. No one can deny how good it feels when we see someone like our post or leave a positive comment. The activity causes our brain to produce dopamine, which makes us feel an addictive pleasure.” It is this addiction that leads many people to do work out of thirst or addiction to praise.

“8 But you are not to be called rabbi, for you have one teacher, and you are all brothers. 9 And call no man your father on earth, for you have one Father, who is in heaven. 10 Neither be called instructors, for you have one instructor, the Christ. 11 The greatest among you shall be your servant. 12 Whoever exalts himself will be humbled, and whoever humbles himself will be exalted.”

Many argue that Jesus forbids calling everyone father or denying the role of a father. Notice how he uses the honored titles of Rabbi, Father (possibly from Matthew 3:9, referring to Abraham’s claim to be the father of the hypocritical Pharisees), and Leader (referring to Moses because they occupied Moses’ seat) by using the word “do not”. This is also not to say that pastors should not be called Pastor, Father, Leader or Professor, because Jesus was talking about the motive of a proud heart, not the designation.

**Rev. Hermawan**
Deacon at PAC Jakarta
    `
